          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 18371,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "CER welcomes the European Commission's initiative to develop a Digital Fairness Act (DFA) to address the identified gaps and areas of legal uncertainty concerning consumer protection online. We support the goal of protecting customers from problematic practices and promoting a fairer digital environment. The overall objective of ensuring fairness for consumers and businesses in business-to-consumer transactions in the digital single market, improving legal certainty, and preventing market fragmentation is crucial for the railway sector, which is increasingly engaging with customers through online channels.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s3",
          "section_path": [
            "CER",
            "Digital Fairness Act"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 84,
          "char_len": 613
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p8",
        "items": [
          {
            "topic": "Design Patterns",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "dark patterns"
              },
              {
                "quote": "addictive design features"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "topic": "Personalisation",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "unfair personalisation practices"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 11321,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "Nevertheless, it will be of utmost importance to define the scope of the Digital Fairness Act adequately to target problematic practices without hindering useful and widely adopted measures that benefit consumers. Specifically, while we support the Commission's intent to tackle issues such as dark patterns, addictive design features, and unfair personalisation practices, we must caution against including common and transparent retail practices within the scope of the DFA where no potential consumer harm has been identified.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s3",
          "section_path": [
            "CER",
            "Digital Fairness Act"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 76,
          "char_len": 529
        }
      },
